4":"1174","1151":"1151","1180":"1180","1128":"1128","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1104":"1104","1145":"1145","about 1139":"about 1139","1166":"1166","about 1104":"about 1104","about 1145":"about 1145","about 1174":"about 1174","1108":"1108","Stoke Damerel, Devon, England":"Stoke Damerel, Devon, England","Moulton, Lincolnshire, England":"Moulton, Lincolnshire, England","Stoke, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stoke, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Reviers, Calvados, Basse-Normandie, France":"Reviers, Calvados, Lower Normandy, France","Devonport, Plymouth, Devon, England":"Devonport, Plymouth, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Briwere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Pierre, Adrien, Aurele, Benedicte, Benoit, Colette, Fernand, Gaston, Marcel, Micheline.","French (<b>Brière</b>): topographic name from a regional variant of Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’ (see   Bruyere  ), or a habitational name from La Brière, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France, from the same word.","History: Jean Brière from Clarbec in Calvados, France, married Jeanne Grandin in Quebec City, QC, in 1671."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruyere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Jacques, Marcel.","French (<b>Bruyère</b>): from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heather’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived in a place where heather grew, or a habitational name from one of the places in France (for example in Calvados) named with this word. Compare   Labruyere  .","Altered form (<b>Bruyère</b>) of French <b>Bruguier</b>: habitational name from (Le) Bruguier, the name of several places in the southeastern part of France, a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":2,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Briwere was born about 1104, in Stoke Damerel, Devon, England. He married Joan Vernon de Reviers in 1128, in Stoke